<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-312-764  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 312 764.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 29 1989 v23 n22 p84(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Clearing desks for scanners: falling prices, more software helpfuel popularity of low-end machines.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burden, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Price cuts and software improvements are driving the growth ofdesktop scanners.andP;  Venture Development Corp, a market researchfirm, predicts that unit shipments of these scanners will increase33 percent per year in the coming years, with sales rising from36,000 units in 1988 to approximately 120,000 in 1992.andP;  Ventureattributes this growth to the scanners' declining prices.andP;  Desktopscanners now cost anywhere from $200 to $10,000, depending ontheir power, and Venture expects annual declines in price of up to12 percent.andP;  Desktop scanners are also becoming more popular dueto the availability of improved scanning software.andP;  Scanningsoftware that reside on microcomputers allows better control overresolution and the number of gray tones than traditional line artscanning packages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     GrowthScanningPriceSoftware PackagesMarket Share.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Desktop scanner prices, 1987-1992. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>